# Health Basics O/X
> Everyday facts about the human body and health
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.health-medical.basic/

The human heart pumps blood throughout the body. | O | The heart works like a pump, circulating blood to every part of the body.
Antibiotics are effective at killing the virus that causes the common cold. | X | Antibiotics work on bacteria, not viruses like the common cold.
Regular exercise benefits cardiovascular health. | O | Consistent exercise strengthens the heart and blood vessels.
Humans have only one lung, located on the right side of the body. | X | Humans have two lungs, one on each side of the chest.
Adequate sleep supports the immune system. | O | Getting enough sleep helps the immune system work properly.
Vitamin C is a fat-soluble vitamin that builds up heavily in body fat. | X | Vitamin C is water-soluble, so excess amounts leave the body in urine.
Washing hands regularly helps prevent the spread of infections. | O | Hand-washing removes germs and reduces the spread of infections.
Normal adult body temperature is around 42 degrees Celsius. | X | Normal body temperature is about 37 degrees Celsius; 42 would be dangerous.
The skin is the largest organ of the human body. | O | By surface area, the skin is the body's largest organ.
Smoking has no connection to lung cancer. | X | Smoking is strongly linked to lung cancer and many other diseases.
Drinking water is essential for the human body to function. | O | Water is vital for digestion, temperature control, and many body functions.
The brain can function normally for hours without any oxygen. | X | The brain is very sensitive to a lack of oxygen and is harmed within minutes.
The adult human body has 206 bones. | O | A typical adult skeleton is made up of 206 bones.
Cracking your knuckles causes arthritis. | X | The popping sound comes from gas bubbles in the joint fluid, and studies have not linked it to arthritis.
The liver can regenerate lost tissue. | O | The liver is unusual among organs in its ability to regrow tissue after part of it is removed or damaged.
Humans only use 10 percent of their brains. | X | This is a myth; brain scans show that virtually all parts of the brain are active at some point.
Human blood is always red and is never truly blue. | O | Blood is red because of hemoglobin; veins can look blue through the skin, but the blood inside is still red.
Eating lots of carrots gives you dramatically better than normal night vision. | X | Carrots supply vitamin A needed for healthy eyes, but they do not push vision beyond normal levels.
The stomach produces acid that helps digest food. | O | Stomach acid breaks down food and helps kill many ingested germs.
Shaving hair makes it grow back thicker and darker. | X | Shaving cuts hair at the surface and does not change its thickness or color; regrowth only feels coarse at first.
Vaccines help the body build immunity to specific diseases. | O | Vaccines train the immune system to recognize and fight a germ before a real infection occurs.
Reading in dim light permanently damages your eyes. | X | Reading in dim light can cause temporary eye strain but does not cause lasting damage.
A resting adult heart usually beats about 60 to 100 times per minute. | O | A normal resting heart rate for adults falls roughly between 60 and 100 beats per minute.
Humans can go for weeks with no sleep at all and stay perfectly healthy. | X | Sleep is essential; going without it for long causes serious impairment and can be dangerous.
Calcium is important for building strong bones and teeth. | O | Calcium is a key mineral that helps form and maintain bones and teeth.
Cold weather by itself is what causes the common cold. | X | Colds are caused by viruses, not by cold temperatures, though people gather indoors more in winter.
The small intestine is longer than the large intestine. | O | The small intestine is several meters long, much longer than the large intestine.
Drinking alcohol raises your body's core temperature to keep you warm. | X | Alcohol widens skin blood vessels so you feel warm, but it actually lowers core body temperature.
A fever is one of the body's natural responses to infection. | O | Raising body temperature helps the immune system fight off invading germs.
Muscle turns into fat when you stop exercising. | X | Muscle and fat are different tissues; muscle can shrink and fat can grow, but one does not convert into the other.
Dietary fiber aids digestion. | O | Fiber adds bulk and helps food move through the digestive tract.
Type O negative blood cannot be given to anyone else. | X | O negative is the universal donor type and can be given to patients of any blood type in emergencies.
Too much salt in the diet can raise blood pressure. | O | High salt intake can increase blood pressure in many people, raising heart risks.
Sitting too close to a television causes permanent blindness. | X | Sitting close may tire the eyes but does not cause lasting damage or blindness.
Sunscreen helps protect skin from ultraviolet damage. | O | Sunscreen blocks or absorbs UV rays, reducing sunburn and long-term skin damage.
The heart sits entirely on the left side of the chest. | X | The heart lies near the center of the chest, tilted slightly to the left, not entirely on the left.
